<?xml version="1.0"?>

<Civ4Defines xmlns="x-schema:CIV4GlobalDefinesSchema.xml">
	<!-- [advc.104x] This file used to be called BBAI_AI_Variables_
		 GlobalDefines.xml; now also contains UWAI parameters.

		 UWAI breaks down the computation of AI war utility into a sum of
		 28 "aspects", most of which are either in favor of war (added to the
		 total war utility) or against war (subtracted). There are a few mixed
		 aspects that could either increase or decrease war utility.
		 Each aspect corresponds to one particular motivation for or against war.
		 Through this file, a weight is assigned to each aspect. This weight is
		 interpreted as a percentage by which the aspect utility is multiplied.
		 The default (recommended) weights are all 100. This doesn't imply though
		 that all aspects contribute equally by default; the weights are only a
		 final adjustment to the (hardcoded) formulas.
		 A weight of e.g. 50 halves the default impact of an aspect, 200
		 doubles it. 0 means that the aspect is entirely disregarded. A
		 negative weight (not recommended) turns a pro-war aspect into an
		 anti-war aspect or vice versa.
		 In the descriptions below, "we" refers to the AI civ that is
		 considering war. -->
	<Define>
		<!-- The cities we expect to conquer as economic assets. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_GREED_FOR_ASSETS</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- The economic value of accepted capitulations. 
			 (Not: Getting closer to a Conquest victory; that's handled under
			  MILITARY_VICTORY.) -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_GREED_FOR_VASSALS</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- By eliminating a civ early in the game, some of the unsettled land
			 near it can be settled and exploited. Lebensraum if you will (and
			 in Civ, it actually works).  -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_GREED_FOR_SPACE</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Just the value of expected reparations really. Sponsored war is
			 covered by HIRED_HAND. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_GREED_FOR_CASH</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- The satisfaction of seeing our (worst) enemies devastated. -->
		<!-- custom: seeing worst enemy defeated should not matter as much as seeing
		ourselves grow maybe, decreasing this a bit so hopefully AI is a bit more
		effective, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_LOATHING</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>70</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- The prospect of a speedy military victory incites us to wage war.
			 This covers Domination, Conquest and Diplomatic victory; Diplo
			 victory also factors into ILL_WILL. -->
		<!-- custom: slightly increase war propension if we are likely to win, but
		not increasing it a lot, as there is a risk too of going too soon to war
		(exposure to other rivals, risk if war fails, slower economy short term,
		was 100)-->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_MILITARY_VICTORY</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>105</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Protect our partners because we want to continue trading with
			 them, and don't want to become isolated. Assistance for more
			 principled reasons is covered by FIDELITY, the "mutual struggle"
			 diplo bonus by SUCKING_UP. -->
		<!-- custom: as much as we like our partners, it is in our interest if
		rivals fight each other, we conquer back the cities they lost, liberate
		it for them to gain favour, or keep it as our expansion, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_PRESERVATION_OF_PARTNERS</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>80</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
  <!-- The next four - Reconquista, Rebuke, Fidelity and Hired Hand - are about
	   upholding a reputation. Since Civ 4 doesn't have a reputation system,
	   this is mostly (irrational) role-playing. -->
	<Define>
		<!-- By reconquering previously owned cities, we show that it's not
			 worthwhile to conquer our cities; we'll get them back. -->
		<!-- custom: city has our culture, so worth more and easier to benefit from
		than a rival's city. It may sometimes be wise to give up the city short	term
		or even mid or long term maybe too sometimes so not increasing it a lot,
		was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_RECONQUISTA</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>110</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- We show we can take by force what was denied to us when we
			 demanded tribute. I.e. increased war utility if we remember how
			 they "refused to give us tribute". A rebuked demand can also lead
			 to an immediate change in war planning, but that's handled by
			 WarAndPeaceAI::Team::respondToRebuke, not in XML. -->
		<!-- custom: tribute is not just for show, hopefully this maybe also
		improves immersion, however AI demands are sometimes ridiculous,
		so increase it only a bit. It does currently feel that they would
		never ever declare war even though they have reason to (according to
		what they think/value it seems i think maybe), was 100. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_REBUKE</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>110</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- By declaring war on a civ that recently attacked one of our
			 partners, we demonstrate that it's worthwhile to be our partner,
			 and dangerous to attack our partners. -->
		<!-- custom: may make the early game more interesting and also punish
		overexpanding/overwarmongering players that may have been a bit too
		careless about their defenses while doing so, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_FIDELITY</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>110</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- We continue a war because we've been paid for it. (Or maybe, rather,
			 to prove that we're a reliable hireling.) -->
		<!-- custom: just because we are paid for a war is no incentive to risk
		weakening our mainland, incentive should be more focused on potential
		gains (vs risk of loss), was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_HIRED_HAND</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>0</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- By conquering cities, we reduce culture pressure on our cities. -->
		<!-- custom: some culture pressure is maybe better than a war, especially if
		mid late game, at this point rivals would just/more be neighbours (more
		realistic/immersive too this way i think maybe), so make AI more likely to
		tolerate it, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_BORDER_DISPUTES</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>90</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Fight a joint war for the "mutual struggle" diplo bonus. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_SUCKING_UP</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- To weaken a civ that we perceive as a long-term military threat. -->
		<!-- custom: may help AI attack sooner a rival that blocks its expansion?,
		was 100-->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_PREEMPTIVE_WAR</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>125</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Stop civs that we don't like from winning the game, or even civs
			 that we're Pleased with if we're in contention ourselves. Likely
			 winners can be civs close to a victory condition, but also civs
			 that have gotten ahead in score or that we expect to get ahead
			 through an ongoing war. -->
		<!-- custom: more so that they are kept in check and punished sooner for
		running away with the game without taking necessary/some preparations,
		may also make the game more dynamic and less one-sided for more immersion
		possibly too, was 100-->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_KING_MAKING</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>105</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Our military build-up, lost units and ravages of war. Adjusted
			 based on our opportunities for peaceful development (i.e. it's an
			 opportunity cost). Also takes into account whether we'll have
			 further use of units surviving the war and whether lost units
			 will have to be replaced. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_EFFORT</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- The risk of losing cities or vassals in the war, or even having to
			 capitulate or being eliminated. -->
		<!-- custom: slightly increase this to prevent excessive war declarations
		(that may backfire for the AI maybe), was 100-->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_RISK</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>105</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- The negative diplomatic consequences of war: angering the civ
			 we're fighting against and third parties. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_ILL_WILL</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Don't want to plan war against civs that we like. This is only
			 role-playing; ILL_WILL handles the rational reasons for not
			 attacking partners. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_AFFECTION</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Distractions from fighting multiple wars are already covered by
			 the military analysis, but not quite reliably, so this is an
			 extra cost to discourage wars on multiple fronts. -->
		<!-- custom: AI is unlikely to win 2+ wars at the same time, almost always
		likely to end bad for the AI, so may help the AI to further discourage
		it, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_DISTRACTION</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>300</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Anger from war weariness and bonds of faith. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_PUBLIC_OPPOSITION</DefineName>
		<!-- custom: should matter less if war is short or/and conquered city has
		new ressources, was 100 -->
		<iDefineIntVal>50</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- War leaves fewer units stationed in cities, which can lead to
			 revolts in cities conquered in some previous war. Due to the
			 "Immortal Culture" changes, this consideration is sometimes
			 significant. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_REVOLTS</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Applies only when we're paid to start a war and the sponsor isn't
			 apparently in need of assistance (or not even at war). Why hire
			 us then? Will have to pay extra to allay our suspicions. -->
		<!-- custom: need to pay more to make us going to war for/with someone
		as it is more likely to bite us back (or we'd be manipulated in doing
		so), was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_ULTERIOR_MOTIVES</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>200</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Discourages early war against humans; not fair when the AI has a
			 head start. -->
		<!-- custom: give a bit more time for the human player to catch up, but
		not too much. Hopefully this also helps prevent suicidal war declarations
		that are done too soon and do not profit the player that declared war vs
		the rivals developing their economy in the early game instead, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_FAIR_PLAY</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>125</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- War as its own purpose. Before this aspect was added, there was too
			 little war before the Medieval era on spacious maps.
			 Especially affects AI leaders with aggressive/ suicidal
			 personalities. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_BELLICOSITY</DefineName>
		<!-- custom: the human player (and other players too) can't just play it
		safe and focus only on economy for ultra late game win, this should be
	    punished by players that are strong enough to profit from that immediate
		advantage, and the human or other players should instead have a more
		balanced approach and be aware of that, was 100 -->
		<iDefineIntVal>120</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Is the tactical situation favorable, i.e. do we/ do they have
			 exposed damaged units, cities that are about to fall, or
			 reinforcements coming up. When in doubt, entangled units lead to
			 increased war utility. If still preparing war: Do we have suffi-
			 cient units to start the war; is there still enough time to build
			 them? -->
		<!-- custom: hopefully helps the AI have a more dynamic or/and
		opportunistic response to local position, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_TACTICAL_SITUATION</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>140</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Pacifism for humanitarian reasons (roleplaying). This is different
			 from Affection, which only applies if we don't dislike them too
			 much and, in particular, not when already at war.
			 Love of Peace subtracts our iLoveOfPeace (Civ4LeaderHeadInfos.xml)
			 from our war utility. When already at war, only half of that is
			 subtracted. iLoveOfPeace is unused in AdvCiv, so this aspect
			 exists only for mod-mods. -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_LOVE_OF_PEACE</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>100</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
	<!-- We're wary of waging war when a dangerous third party appears likely
		 to intervene against us. -->
		<!-- custom: overexpansion would kill the player, so some caution if
		outnumbered	may help a lot, possibly the player being outnumbered to
		make a comeback later too?, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_THIRD_PARTY_INTERVENTION</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>200</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
	<!-- To keep the game entertaining for human players, we're more inclined
		 to start a war if none has been fought among civs known to us for a
		 long time. Conversely, we're more inclined to make peace if many wars
		 have been ongoing for a long time. -->
		<!-- custom: focus should be more on actual gains and risks of losses,
		not on entertaining the human player especially if doing a foolish war
		declaration	that would later be exploited by other players, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_WEIGHT_DRAMATIC_ARC</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>10</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>

	<Define>
		<!-- Recommended: 100 (BtS behavior)
			 If this percentage is less than 100, all AI personality values
			 from Civ4LeaderHeadInfos.xml are moved toward their median. Formula:
			 ((UWAI_PERSONALITY_PERCENT * x +
			 (100 - UWAI_PERSONALITY_PERCENT) * m) / 100
			 where x is a personality value of a given leader and m the median
			 over all leader personalities defined in XML (except the Barbarian
			 leader). E.g. UWAI_PERSONALITY_PERCENT=50 moves the values halfway
			 to the  median, making the AI personalities half as pronounced.
			 0 eliminates the personalities (apart from traits). Favorite civic
			 and religion are normally unaffected, but, in the special case of
			 UWAI_PERSONALITY_PERCENT=0, all leaders are set to having no
			 favorites. (They'll still "care for their brothers and sisters of
			 the faith" though.) UWAI_PERSONALITY_PERCENT>100 makes the
			 personalities more pronounced (not tested). Negative values invert
			 the personalities (not tested and not recommended). -->
		<!-- custom: have personalities be more pronounced (experimental), maybe
		it would make the game more entertaining, or games in general more
		varied, without affecting as much effectiveness of decisions as compared
		to dramatic_war?, was 100 -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_PERSONALITY_PERCENT</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>120</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<!-- [/advc.104x] -->
	<!-- [advc.104] Misc. UWAI parameters -->
	<Define>
		<!-- Added to the utility threshold for starting a war while already in
			 a war. Recommended: 10 (or sth. between 0 and 25). -->
		<!-- custom: testing 25, would this make AIs less willing/likely to fight
		multi wars, thus increasing AI efficiency?, was 10-->
		<!-- custom: now i want to increase this more to see, seemed to perform
		quite well in the (few) tests i made, was 25 last time i changed it,
		not to totally prevent it, but very strongly discourage it, it really
		should be very bad for the AI to fight multi wars in terms of wining
		i mean, as for roleplaying it is not my core concern at least about this
		point that affects AI performance meaning its strength i mean, i think,
		was 25 last time i modified it -->
		<DefineName>UWAI_MULTI_WAR_RELUCTANCE</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>50</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
    <Define>
		<!-- When computing per-civ power values (which play an important role
			 in decisions on war and peace), the power value of each individual
			 unit is raised to the power of (i.e. exponentiated by)
			 POWER_CORRECTION. For example, if POWER_CORRECTION is 200%, per-unit
			 power values are squared. POWER_CORRECTION = 100% is the BtS behavior;
			 power values then typically equal unit strength, e.g. two Warriors
			 are as good as one Spearman. When squaring, one Spearman is as
			 good as four Warriors. (That seems too much.) Recommended:
			 166%; one Spearman then corresponds to 3.15 Warriors. -->
		<!-- advc.159: A fraction (3/4) of this value is also used for some
			 tactical decisions outside the UWAI component. -->
		<!-- custom: Extra checking the kmod value:
		2^1.66 = 3.160 and 4^1.66 = 9.987 , so one spearman is as strong, corrected,
		as 9.987 / 3.160 = 3.160 (too) warriors, same as kmod value indeed so my
		math is hopefully correct in this case at least i mean anyways.

		Now changing it to a maybe more fit for my purpose value or how i think
		it may fit better the game:
		2^1.59 = 3.010 strength corrected and 4^1.59 = 9.063
		approximately so a spearman (basing myself on base bts/advic strength,
		just as an example mostly used to illustrate the math a bit i mean
		anyways) is closer to 3	(9.063 / 3.010 = 3.011 , to be more exact
		(still approximate)) warriors now, so maybe this is good enough odds
		to consider attacking with the 3 warriors now?
		May also help AI stacks	not stare at each other too long and start city
		attacks sooner?
		
		Increased it to 160 to be safer (than 159), so one warrior is
		2^1.6 = 3.031 corrected strength now and one spearman is 4^1.6 = 9.190
		corrected strength now,	and so one spearman	is now as worth as
		9.190 / 3.031 = 3.032 warriors, which is maybe a bit safer,
		was 166 -->
        <DefineName>POWER_CORRECTION</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>160</iDefineIntVal>
    </Define>
	<!-- [/advc.104] -->

	<!-- -->
	<!-- Better BTS AI / K-Mod variables to allow easy AI tweaking -->
	<!-- by jdog5000 / karadoc -->
	<!-- -->
	<Define> <!-- redefine -->
		<!-- War success value of capturing a city.  BBAI: 25, BtS 10
		advc.130r: Reduce a little. Caveat: Should be careful about
		changing this value, it's used as a baseline in many places. -->
		<DefineName>WAR_SUCCESS_CITY_CAPTURING</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>22</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Ratio of enemy power to team power for AI to consider
		running TURTLE (all out defense, no offensive forays) strategy.
		Equal power would be 100.  BBAI default: 250 -->
		<!-- custom: try turtling sooner to avoid a too late to defend
		situation. I would want to reduce further this value but would
		need more changes, as in some cases AI turtles too much early
		just because one player that is	sometimes far from them produces
		(way) more units than the other players. Maybe this creates a
		vicious loop where the "angry" unit pomper (think montezuma/
		khmer/boudica AI in the early game maybe as an example maybe
		if i am not mistaken i mean) sees that they have now less and
		(in their perception) not enough units (more) than the other
		rivals, so they produce	more, inducing the other players to
		produce more etc.
		To prevent that, i am putting the value higher than i would
		want to, at	160	currently.
		Ideally	if higher than 110 power ratio the AI should start
		to turtle, else it's a big	gamble to bet on not being attacked
		(for what reason i	mean anyways?), especially with my changes
		that aim at making the AI more pragmatic and opportunistic, to
		increase its strength and realism too maybe i mean, so that i
		can enjoy the game more and hopefully others if they try these
		changes i made and want a similar type of gameplay (else they
		may tweak or not it as they see fit maybe i mean)), was 250 -->
		<DefineName>BBAI_TURTLE_ENEMY_POWER_RATIO</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>160</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Minimum stack strength ratio at which AI will attack enemy
		city it is next to, higher means less suicide.
		BTS default: 120, BBAI: 125, now: 123 -->
		<!-- custom: many times AI troops are too long to start an
		attack and keep staring at	each other, facilitate a bit more
		the AI attack to start, was 123 -->
		<DefineName>BBAI_ATTACK_CITY_STACK_RATIO</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>122</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<!-- advc.003j: Obsoleted by K-Mod code (CvUnitAI::AI_bombardCity) -->
	<!-- Minimum attack odds of best attacker for AI to skip bombarding 
	a city and just attack.  BBAI default: 12 -->
	<!--Define>
		<DefineName>BBAI_SKIP_BOMBARD_BEST_ATTACK_ODDS</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>10</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define-->
	<Define>
		<!-- Base ratio of stack strengths for AI considering skipping
		bombard	and just attacking enemy city. This ratio is reduced by
		the AI's best attacker odds and how long it will take to bombard
		the city.
		Lower means AI will more readily skip bombarding.
		BBAI default: 300 -->
		<!-- advc.114c: Was 260 in K-Mod, now 250. -->
		<!-- custom: speed up a bit the early conquest, later in the
		game having	a good pace/tempo and short war should also be
		valuable for the AI, would give less time to build more defenders
		while city is bombarded too so maybe it balances itself out this
		way -->
		<DefineName>BBAI_SKIP_BOMBARD_BASE_STACK_RATIO</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>240</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Minimum stack strength ratio for AI to skip bombarding city
		and	just attack, higher is more conservative.  BBAI default: 150 -->
		<!-- advc.114c: Was 140 in K-Mod, now 137. -->
		<!-- custom: similar as for skip_bombard_base_stack_ratio, to
		facilitate a bit more early attack, with in mind the possible
		benefits of doing so too, was 137 -->
		<DefineName>BBAI_SKIP_BOMBARD_MIN_STACK_RATIO</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>135</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
	<Define>
		<!-- Minimum city site value that the AI will consider settling.
		default: 600. (K-Mod) -->
		<!-- custom: at first i thought some cities are not good enough
		but AI still settles them and cripples itself, hopefully this
		improves that while not hurting AI growth too much, but it didn't
		seem to do too much especially if increased too much. A very low
		value (around 300 for example) seemed to be mostly ignored too
		(except AI had more cities that were a bit too crammed.
		Trying other values, it seems 550 somehow, i don't know why, but
		consistently provides better city spots to the AI, would need
		more testing to make sure., was 600 -->
		<DefineName>BBAI_MINIMUM_FOUND_VALUE</DefineName>
		<iDefineIntVal>550</iDefineIntVal>
	</Define>
</Civ4Defines>